INTRODUCING RUSSIA'S NEW ASSOCIATION FOR INTERNATIONAL EDUCATION
________________________________________________________________

     This new non-governmental, not-for-profit  association of Russian and
international educational organisations was created in 1993.


The principal goals of the Association:

*       To identify and focus the experience and efforts of Russian
        educational institutions;
*       To establish close ties with international institutions,
        universities and donor organisations;
*       To facilitate of academic mobility between universities;
*       To assist participating institutions in granting degrees;
*       To support the development of innovative educational methods,
        e.g., distance learning, academic exchanges and application of
        communications technologies.


The following institutions and organisations are founders of the Association:

*       Russian Federation State Committee for Higher Education (Ministry);
*       Information Systems Research Institute of Russia (ISRIR);
*       Moscow State Institute of Electronics and Mathematics (MIEM)
*	Moscow State University of Forestry;
*	Moscow Peoples' Friendship University;
*	Moscow State Pedagogical University;
*       Moscow State Aviation Technology University;
*       International Centre of Continuing Education''Postgraduate" and
*       Moscow Municipal Experimental Centre of Computer Learning


The Association is deeply committed to supporting  the  development of
Distance Education in Russia.

        Both experience and ongoing reviews demonstrate convincingly that
the distance form of education  offers  an  extremely important tool within
the Russian context. Many initiatives are underway to ensure the maximum
benefit from the use of these techniques, for instance:

        This year AIE is administering a nationwide competition on
"Information technologies of distance education and their application in
learning". The best projects will get the financial awards provided by AIE.

        In July 5-8 AIE is presenting the First International Conference
on distance education in Russia "Distance learning and new technologies
in education". Michael Moore, Editor of the American Journal of Distance
Education, is a Chairman of the International Program Committee, and
Alexander Tikhonov, the First Deputy Chairman of the Russian Federation
State Committee on Higher Education, is a Chairman of National Organising
Committee.

        The State University of New York (SUNY) is conducting a pilot
project of distance graduate level education for eight MIEM students,
leading to the award of SUNY Master's degree in Computer  Science.
Previously taken  MIEM courses were included in the program,  and
supplemented by courses developed at  the  SUNY  Institute  of  Technology.
The United States Information  Agency  (USIA)  granted $150,000  to  SUNY
for the early development of the project.  A second key element  of  the
effort  is cooperation  with the Association in the creation and operation
of the Moscow Distance Learning Centre at MIEM.

        USIA has officially  declared  Distance Education  to  be  one  of
primary  components of its evolving support programs in Russia. Also, the
Commission of European Union has expressed its interest in the development
of Distance Education in Russia, and Distance Education is recognised by
the World Bank to be  one  of  the  most  effective  and accessible
mechanisms for training and retraining in this country.

        Digital Equipment Corporation donated a VAX 4000/200 mini-computer
to the Moscow Institute of Electronics and Mathematics, thus forming  the
core  of  an  expanding  local area network dedicated to the instruction of
students  at  the  Distance  Learning Centre.

The Association serves as an information focal point in the area of
International Education.

        AIE runs an electronic information service providing access via
Internet to numerous universities, scientific research institutes,
governmental agencies and companies. The USIA information board, the Russian
Federation State Committee for Higher Education official information
directory, and the International Centre of Distance Learning (UK Open
University) database are among the available resources.

        To access the information, send a message with the word HELP to
the address ms@aie.msk.su.
        AIE is creating an International Education Library comprising books
on education, information on institutions, case studies, and statistics.

        The Association is working out a foreign languages testing service.

The International Institute for Business Communication (Japan) and AIE have a
Commitment to setup a network of Test of English for International
Communication (TOEIC) testing and training sites. It assumes active
cooperation with Educational Testing Service and Russian universities.

	Pushkin Institute of Russian Language and Literature (Moscow) is 
developing a Test of Russian as a Foreign Language to introduce it
in AIE international projects.

	The Association runs a number of academic exchange programs.
They mean: undergraduate-, graduate-level education of Russian students 
at foreign universities; languages training programs (including TOEFL 
preparation and testing abroad); education and training of foreign stu-
dents in Russia (including Russian language training and testing)

